{{Infobox organization
| name = Shinshū Takada-ha
| native_name = 真宗高田派
| image = [[File:Shinshu Takada-ha Shumuin.JPG|250px]]
| caption = The Religious Affairs Office at the head temple [[Senjuji]]
| type = [[Religious corporation]]
| headquarters = 2819 Isshinden-chō, Tsu City, Mie Prefecture
| leader_title = Hōshu (Head Priest)
| leader_name = Jishō
| website = {{URL|http://www.senjuji.or.jp/}}
}}

'''Shinshū Takada-ha''' (真宗高田派) is a branch of {{ill|Jōdo Shinshū|ja|淡土真宗|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōdo Shinshū|qq=}}, with its head temple at {{ill|Senjuji|ja|專修寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senjuji|qq=}} in {{ill|Tsu, Mie|ja|渡哥市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsu, Mie|qq=}}. It traces its origins to the disciples {{ill|Shinbutsu|ja|真仏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu|qq=}} and {{ill|Kenchi|ja|顕智|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kenchi|qq=}}, who led the Highada-monto community in the medieval period. The sect has approximately 640 affiliated temples.

== History ==

=== Founding Period ===
In {{ill|1205|ja|1205th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1205|qq=}}, during the reign of {{ill|Emperor Go-Toba|ja|後鳥羽天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Go-Toba|qq=}}, the practice of {{ill|Senju Nembutsu|ja|専修念仏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senju Nembutsu|qq=}}, propagated by {{ill|Hōnen|ja|法然|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōnen|qq=}} and his disciples, was banned, leading to the exile of {{ill|Shinran|ja|親熊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinran|qq=}} to {{ill|Echigo Province|ja|越後国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Echigo Province|qq=}}. After being pardoned in {{ill|1211|ja|1211th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1211|qq=}}, Shinran traveled to {{ill|Zenkoji|ja|善光寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zenkoji|qq=}} and then settled in {{ill|Hitachi Province|ja|常陽国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hitachi Province|qq=}}, where he began his missionary activities.

Shinran established his base at {{ill|Nishi Nembutsuji|ja|西念仏寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishi Nembutsuji|qq=}} in Hitachi, and in {{ill|1224|ja|1224th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1224|qq=}}, he completed his seminal work, {{ill|Kyōgyōshinshō|ja|顯淡土真実教行証文類|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyōgyōshinshō|qq=}} ('Teaching, Practice, Faith, and Attainment'), which laid the doctrinal foundation for Jōdo Shinshū.

In {{ill|1225|ja|1225th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1225|qq=}}, according to tradition, Shinran received a revelation instructing him to establish a temple in Highada. With the support of {{ill|Ōuchi Clan|ja|大内氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōuchi Clan|qq=}}, the ruler of {{ill|Mooka Castle|ja|真岡城|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mooka Castle|qq=}}, he enshrined a replica of the {{ill|Zenkoji-style Amida Triad|ja|善光寺式阿弥陀三宗|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zenkoji-style Amida Triad|qq=}} in what became {{ill|Senjuji|ja|專修寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senjuji|qq=}}, marking the origins of the Highada-monto tradition and the Shinshū Takada-ha sect.

The temple was officially named ''Senshū Amida-ji'' in {{ill|1226|ja|1226年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1226|qq=}} by imperial decree, and Shinran spent about seven years there before returning to Kyoto. After Shinran's departure, his prominent disciple {{ill|Shinbutsu|ja|真仏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu|qq=}} succeeded him as the second head priest of Senjuji, followed by {{ill|Kenchi|ja|顕智|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kenchi|qq=}}.

=== Sengoku Period ===
During the 15th century, the sect expanded significantly under the leadership of the 10th head priest, {{ill|Shin'e|ja|真恵|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shin'e|qq=}}, who actively spread Jōdo Shinshū teachings across {{ill|Tōkai region|ja|東海地方|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tōkai region|qq=}} and {{ill|Hokuriku region|ja|北陸地方|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hokuriku region|qq=}}. However, conflicts arose with {{ill|Rennyo|ja|蓮妃|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rennyo|qq=}}, the influential head of {{ill|Honganji|ja|本願寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Honganji|qq=}}, leading many followers and temples to shift allegiance to the Honganji faction. In {{ill|1465|ja|1465th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1465|qq=}}, Shin'e petitioned {{ill|Mount Hiei|ja|比士山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Hiei|qq=}} to recognize Takada-ha as separate from Honganji, which was granted.

Despite setbacks due to military conflicts, including the {{ill|Echizen Ikkō-Ikki|ja|越前一向一挑|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Echizen Ikkō-Ikki|qq=}}, Takada-ha retained a strong presence in certain regions. By the 16th century, the sect moved its primary temple from {{ill|Shimotsuke Province|ja|下野国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimotsuke Province|qq=}} to {{ill|Isshinden|ja|一身田|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Isshinden|qq=}} in {{ill|Ise Province|ja|伊勢国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise Province|qq=}}, where it remains today.

=== Edo Period ===
During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo period|qq=}}, Takada-ha maintained its status as one of the largest Jōdo Shinshū sects after the split of {{ill|Honganji|ja|本願寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Honganji|qq=}} into the {{ill|Nishi Honganji|ja|西本願寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishi Honganji|qq=}} and {{ill|Higashi Honganji|ja|東本願寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Higashi Honganji|qq=}} branches. The sect continued to flourish, with its head temple, Senjuji, recognized as a ''jun-monzeki'' (quasi-imperial temple).

== Major Temples ==
; Head Temple
* {{ill|Senjuji|ja|專修寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senjuji|qq=}} (Mooka, Tochigi Prefecture)

; Main Temple
* {{ill|Senjuji|ja|專修寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senjuji|qq=}} (Isshinden, Tsu, Mie Prefecture)

; Branch Temples
* Kyoto Betsuin
* {{ill|Nagoya Betsuin|ja|專修寺名古屋別院|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagoya Betsuin|qq=}}
* Kobe Betsuin
* Hokkaido Betsuin (Kiyota-ku, Sapporo, Hokkaido)
* Fukui Betsuin
* Kanto Betsuin
* Yokohama Betsuin

== Characteristics ==
Takada-ha uniquely uses ''Bunrui-ge'' ({{ill|Hymns of the Pure Land|ja|文類慰|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hymns of the Pure Land|qq=}}) for evening services, unlike other Jōdo Shinshū sects that primarily recite ''Shōshin-ge'' ({{ill|Hymns of True Faith|ja|正信慰|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hymns of True Faith|qq=}}). Additionally, its temples traditionally do not use {{ill|Tannishō|ja|商異止|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tannishō|qq=}}, as the sect preserves a large collection of Shinran's original writings.

