=== Sengoku Period ===
During the 15th century, the sect expanded significantly under the leadership of the 10th head priest, {{ill|Shin'e|ja|真恵|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shin'e|qq=}}, who actively spread Jōdo Shinshū teachings across {{ill|Tōkai region|ja|東海地方|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tōkai region|qq=}} and {{ill|Hokuriku region|ja|北陸地方|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hokuriku region|qq=}}. However, conflicts arose with {{ill|Rennyo|ja|蓮妃|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rennyo|qq=}}, the influential head of {{ill|Honganji|ja|本願寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Honganji|qq=}}, leading many followers and temples to shift allegiance to the Honganji faction. In {{ill|1465|ja|1465th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1465|qq=}}, Shin'e petitioned {{ill|Mount Hiei|ja|比士山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Hiei|qq=}} to recognize Takada-ha as separate from Honganji, which was granted.

Despite setbacks due to military conflicts, including the {{ill|Echizen Ikkō-Ikki|ja|越前一向一挑|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Echizen Ikkō-Ikki|qq=}}, Takada-ha retained a strong presence in certain regions. By the 16th century, the sect moved its primary temple from {{ill|Shimotsuke Province|ja|下野国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimotsuke Province|qq=}} to {{ill|Isshinden|ja|一身田|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Isshinden|qq=}} in {{ill|Ise Province|ja|伊勢国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise Province|qq=}}, where it remains today.

=== Edo Period ===
During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo period|qq=}}, Takada-ha maintained its status as one of the largest Jōdo Shinshū sects after the split of {{ill|Honganji|ja|本願寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Honganji|qq=}} into the {{ill|Nishi Honganji|ja|西本願寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishi Honganji|qq=}} and {{ill|Higashi Honganji|ja|東本願寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Higashi Honganji|qq=}} branches. The sect continued to flourish, with its head temple, Senjuji, recognized as a ''jun-monzeki'' (quasi-imperial temple).

