'''Shinshū Takada-ha''' (真宗高田派) is a branch of {{ill|Jōdo Shinshū|ja|淡土真宗|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōdo Shinshū|qq=}}, with its head temple at {{ill|Senjuji|ja|專修寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senjuji|qq=}} in {{ill|Tsu, Mie|ja|渡哥市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsu, Mie|qq=}}. It traces its origins to the disciples {{ill|Shinbutsu|ja|真仏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu|qq=}} and {{ill|Kenchi|ja|顕智|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kenchi|qq=}}, who led the Highada-monto community in the medieval period. The sect has approximately 640 affiliated temples.

== History ==

=== Founding Period ===
In [[:en:1205|1205]], during the reign of [[:en:Emperor Go-Toba|Emperor Go-Toba]], the practice of {{ill|Senju Nembutsu|ja|専修念仏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senju Nembutsu|qq=}}, propagated by [[:en:Hōnen|Hōnen]] and his disciples, was banned, leading to the exile of {{ill|Shinran|ja|親熊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinran|qq=}} to [[:en:Echigo Province|Echigo Province]]. After being pardoned in [[:en:1211|1211]], Shinran traveled to [[:en:Zenkō-ji|Zenkoji]] and then settled in {{ill|Hitachi Province|ja|常陽国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hitachi Province|qq=}}, where he began his missionary activities.

Shinran established his base at {{ill|Nishi Nembutsuji|ja|西念仏寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishi Nembutsuji|qq=}} in Hitachi, and in [[:en:1224|1224]], he completed his seminal work, {{ill|Kyōgyōshinshō|ja|顯淡土真実教行証文類|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyōgyōshinshō|qq=}} ('Teaching, Practice, Faith, and Attainment'), which laid the doctrinal foundation for Jōdo Shinshū.

In [[:en:1225|1225]], according to tradition, Shinran received a revelation instructing him to establish a temple in Highada. With the support of [[:en:Ōuchi clan|Ōuchi Clan]], the ruler of {{ill|Mooka Castle|ja|真岡城|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mooka Castle|qq=}}, he enshrined a replica of the {{ill|Zenkoji-style Amida Triad|ja|善光寺式阿弥陀三宗|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zenkoji-style Amida Triad|qq=}} in what became {{ill|Senjuji|ja|專修寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senjuji|qq=}}, marking the origins of the Highada-monto tradition and the Shinshū Takada-ha sect.

The temple was officially named ''Senshū Amida-ji'' in [[:en:1226|1226]] by imperial decree, and Shinran spent about seven years there before returning to Kyoto. After Shinran's departure, his prominent disciple {{ill|Shinbutsu|ja|真仏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu|qq=}} succeeded him as the second head priest of Senjuji, followed by {{ill|Kenchi|ja|顕智|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kenchi|qq=}}.

=== Sengoku Period ===
During the 15th century, the sect expanded significantly under the leadership of the 10th head priest, {{ill|Shin'e|ja|真恵|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shin'e|qq=}}, who actively spread Jōdo Shinshū teachings across [[:en:Tōkai region|Tōkai region]] and [[:en:Hokuriku region|Hokuriku region]]. However, conflicts arose with {{ill|Rennyo|ja|蓮妃|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rennyo|qq=}}, the influential head of {{ill|Honganji|ja|本願寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Honganji|qq=}}, leading many followers and temples to shift allegiance to the Honganji faction. In [[:en:1465|1465]], Shin'e petitioned {{ill|Mount Hiei|ja|比士山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Hiei|qq=}} to recognize Takada-ha as separate from Honganji, which was granted.

Despite setbacks due to military conflicts, including the {{ill|Echizen Ikkō-Ikki|ja|越前一向一挑|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Echizen Ikkō-Ikki|qq=}}, Takada-ha retained a strong presence in certain regions. By the 16th century, the sect moved its primary temple from [[:en:Shimotsuke Province|Shimotsuke Province]] to {{ill|Isshinden|ja|一身田|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Isshinden|qq=}} in [[:en:Ise Province|Ise Province]], where it remains today.

=== Edo Period ===
During the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], Takada-ha maintained its status as one of the largest Jōdo Shinshū sects after the split of {{ill|Honganji|ja|本願寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Honganji|qq=}} into the [[:en:Nishi Hongan-ji|Nishi Honganji]] and [[:en:Higashi Hongan-ji|Higashi Honganji]] branches. The sect continued to flourish, with its head temple, Senjuji, recognized as a ''jun-monzeki'' (quasi-imperial temple).

